<DOC><DOCNO> AP891016-0087 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-16-89 1336EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Glance     10-16 0492</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Scotus-Glance,450</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actionstaken Monday by the Supreme Court.      ANTITRUST      The court agreed to decide whether states, and possibly privatecitizens, may use federal antitrust law to break up corporatemergers.   The court said it will hear arguments by California officialsseeking to scuttle the $2.5 billion merger of the Lucky and AlphaBeta supermarket chains.   Today's action kept in effect an order issued by Justice SandraDay O'Connor in August that blocks completion of the merger.   The case is California vs. American Stores, 89-258.      LAROUCHE      The court turned away an appeal by a political action committeelinked to fringe presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche. It nowfaces having to pay $2.7 million in contempt-of-court fines.   The justices, without comment, refused to hear the NationalDemocratic Policy Committee's challenge to fines stemming from afederal mail fraud and conspiracy prosecution.   The case is National Democratic Policy Committee vs. U.S.,89-320.      UNION DUES      The court rejected an appeal by a right-to-work group thatsought to limit the power of unions to collect dues fromnon-members.   The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments in anIllinois case that the group was treated unfairly by a federalappeals court.   The cases are National Right to Work Foundation vs. AFSME,89-287, and Gilpin vs. AFSCME, 89-292.      PAN AM      The court refused to free Pan American World Airways from havingto pay $951,500 plus interest to two families of 1974 crash victims.   The justices, without comment, left intact the awards stemmingfrom the April 22, 1974, crash in Indonesia of a Pan Am planeflying from Hong Kong to Los Angeles. All 96 passengers and 11 crewmembers died in the accident.   The case is Pan Am vs. Causey, 89-157.      PENALIZING LAWYERS      The court agreed to provide some guidelines for penalizinglawyers who file improper lawsuits.   The court said it will hear an appeal by a Washington, D.C., lawfirm penalized $21,402 for filing an antitrust suit based oninadequate research.   The case is Cooter andamp; Gell vs. Hartmarx Corp., 89-275.      VIDEOTAPED ANSWERS      The court agreed to consider reinstating the drunken drivingconviction of a Pennsylvania man videotaped answering policcequestions about his height, weight and color of his eyes.   The court said it will decide whether police violated themotorist's rights when they videotaped his responses before warninghim of his right to remain silent or have a lawyer present.   The case is Pennsylvania vs. Muniz, 89-213.      INHERITANCE TAXES      The court backed out of deciding whether the Internal RevenueService, when assessing inheritance taxes, may challenge deductionsstate courts have allowed for legal fees and executor's commission.   The justices agreed last February to decide the issue in anappeal by a New York lawyer who acted as executor and attorney fora $450,000 estate.   The case is White vs. U.S., 88-928.</TEXT></DOC>